snippet.textDisplay: I have no idea how End Game didn't win for Visual Effects when it is a total masterclass in visual effects throughout. The sheer scale of what this film achieved from so many talented people is amazing, but it's the on going joke that awards like Oscars and BAFTA are for the elite few and often not for these blockbuster types of films. 1917 is a great film, but when we're focusing on just the visual effects, there's only one winner in my opinion. On another note, I remember when Peter Jackson first suggested this little company called Weta for the effects work on his little indie project about some dwarves and elves etc & some rather important jewellery, and New Line apparently were concerned Weta couldn't pull it off.
snippet.textOriginal: I have no idea how End Game didn't win for Visual Effects when it is a total masterclass in visual effects throughout. The sheer scale of what this film achieved from so many talented people is amazing, but it's the on going joke that awards like Oscars and BAFTA are for the elite few and often not for these blockbuster types of films. 1917 is a great film, but when we're focusing on just the visual effects, there's only one winner in my opinion. On another note, I remember when Peter Jackson first suggested this little company called Weta for the effects work on his little indie project about some dwarves and elves etc & some rather important jewellery, and New Line apparently were concerned Weta couldn't pull it off.

snippet.textDisplay: 11:48 till 13:48 You lost me here: what a giant pile of BS and excuses to justify the CGI. The end result is great and all the team deserves congratulations, but don't call us idiots trying to say the Ironman's head "cut and paste" and the full body digital make over wasn't just laziness. The studio could easily afford a real Ironman suit that matches exactly the digital version so RDJ could wear it at scenes where there is no action ( like when he was about to snap) and makeup and prostetics could easily provide a flawless death appearence, without any complications to camera work because he was all time sit at the same spot and camera ngles were almost static (so no ligthing, reflections, color, proportions issues that can happen at a moving scene). So be honest with yourselves and to the viewers saying "we used CGI there because it is easier than doing the same with real props" . In a near future we will hear things like "We created these actors/actresses, which you can't distinguise from real ones, because that way we can adjust the scenes on the fly and the real ones don't need to repeat many times the same take if the result isn't good from the beggining" , ins tead of being honest and say "Substituting real for digital actors and actresses is cheaper, faster and more reliable than hire real humans."
